<h2>Science Festival</h2>
<h3>Target</h3>
<p>Middle school students from Dandelion Middle School, Daxing District, Beijing.</p>
<h3>Activity Time</h3>
<p>July 19, 2023.</p>
<h3>Purpose</h3>
<p>The Science Festival is a large-scale scientific exchange event held annually during the summer camp at Dandelion Middle School. In the Science Festival, students from each camp set up booths to share and showcase their scientific achievements. As volunteers from the &quot;Get Close to Nature&quot; camp, we had the opportunity to prepare and present our own booth - &quot;Bacteria! Synthetic? Big Challenge!&quot;, to allow more teenagers to learn and understand synthetic biology and experience the fun of biology.</p>
<h3>Preparation：Why did we design the activity in this way?</h3>
<p>As a science outreach event aimed at a wide audience of teenagers, we recognized that many students did not have in-depth knowledge or exposure to synthetic biology. Therefore, we aimed to incorporate a sufficient amount of fun into the potentially dry knowledge. We independently designed a game called &quot;Synthesize Big-gene&quot; (see &quot;Game Development - Targeting the General Public&quot; section for details), guiding students to create bacteria capable of breaking down cellulose. This game was designed to introduce the application concepts of synthetic biology to the participants.</p>
<p>In addition, to spark students&#39; interest in biology, we selected over seventy beautiful and diverse images of animals, plants, and microorganisms from the internet and textbooks. These images were used for the &quot;Prize Quiz&quot; segment at our booth, guiding students to explore the fascinating world of biology and learn about various living organisms.</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/fig17.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 16 &quot;Bacteria! Synthetic? Big Challenge!&quot; science festival booth</center></strong></p>
 
<h3>Process</h3>
<p>Our booth consisted of two activities. The first activity was the &quot;Synthetic Big-gene&quot; game challenge, where members from CAU-China explained the story background of the game (see &quot;Game Development - Targeting the General Public&quot; section for details) and guided participants to play the game on iPad. The students with the highest scores were the winners.</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/fig18.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 17 &quot;Synthetic Big-gene&quot; game challenge</center></strong></p>
<p>The second activity was the &quot;Biological Identification Challenge&quot;, where participants extract an equal number of biological pictures, and the one identifying the most number of species emerged victorious.</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/fig19.png" width="600"/> </div>
 <strong><center>Fig. 18 &quot;Biological Identification Challenge&quot;</center></strong>
 
<p>For the entire morning, we organized dozens of rounds of games. The students from Dandelion Middle School actively participated, and our booth was incredibly lively. Everyone enjoyed themselves thoroughly. In the end, we awarded prizes to the winners, and the students gained a lot from the world of biology.</p>
<h3>Feedback: How did our activities encouraged an open dialogue with audience?</h3>
<h4>For students: what have they learnt from our activities?</h4>
<p>Our synthetic biology-themed booth was widely welcomed by the students of Dandelion Middle School. Not only did the students receive gifts and joy from the games, but they also gained a deeper understanding of the concepts of genes and engineered bacteria. Perhaps among them, there are future talents who will pursue life sciences. For them, today&#39;s &quot;Bacteria! Synthetic? Big Challenge!&quot; must be a wonderful memory.</p>
<p>In the Science Festival organized by Dandelion Middle School, our booth was awarded the &quot;Highest Popularity Index Award.&quot;</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/fig20.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 19 Our booth won the &quot;Highest Popularity Index Award&quot;</center></strong></p>
 
<h4>For CAU-China: what did we received from this activity?</h4>
<p>For the CAU-China team, we were equally surprised by the tremendous popularity our synthetic biology games gained. During the booth activities, many students engaged with us, expressing sentiments like &quot;Synthetic biology is truly magical&quot; and &quot;I didn&#39;t know bacteria could be this amazing&quot;... Amidst the cheers of the students, we felt incredibly inspired. This not only strengthened our determination to pursue the field of synthetic biology but also motivated us to share our project and the wonders of synthetic biology with even more people!</p>
<h4>For the teachers at Dandelion Middle School:what do you want to say to CAU-China?</h4>
<p>&quot;Several students from the CAU-China team volunteered and meticulously prepared exciting courses and activities like &#39;Exploring Synthetic Biology.&#39; With their lively teaching methods and rich knowledge, they not only helped the children understand the mysteries of biology but also sparked their strong interest in science. As biology educators, you showed us more about the cutting-edge areas of biology. In our future classes, we will pay more attention to expanding knowledge, allowing the children to experience the wonders of biology.&quot;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<br><br><div class="container"><div class="horizontal-line"></div></div><h1>Advanced Education - Collision of Ideas Among Peers</h1><div class="container"><div class="horizontal-line"></div></div>
<p>Regardless of time or space, university students are the closest group to us. Therefore, when it comes to university students, we focus on using our team&#39;s project as an example to promote synthetic biology among colleagues interested in biology. Furthermore, students majoring in biology often have a systematic understanding of molecular biology and biochemistry. Hence, in preparing educational activities for this group, we emphasize discussions on professional issues, presentation and explanation of phase achievements of the project, as well as sharing research experiences.</p>
<p>The followings are the educational activities we conducted for college students:</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/fig21.png" width="800"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 20 Educational activities for college students</center></strong></p>
 
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>Camping Activities</h2>
<h3>Target</h3>
<p>Fellow classmates in the same grade biology class.</p>
<h3>Activity Time</h3>
<p>May 29, 2023.</p>
<h3>Purpose</h3>
<p>The proverb goes, &quot;Traveling ten thousand miles is better than reading ten thousand books.&quot; In early summer, several members of CAU-China, along with students from College of Biological Sciences at China Agricultural University&#39;s Biology 211 class, went to Beijing Liudu River to participate in a camping activity. Seizing the opportunity of outdoor activities, we aimed to exchange ideas about our project and synthetic biology with the students, and engage in some fun activities to enhance the camping atmosphere.</p>
<h3>Preparation：Why did we design the activity in this way?</h3>
<p>Our team members and the camping-mates were from the same major and the same grade, so we had a lot of common topics to discuss. However, the camping was a relatively cheerful event, so delivering a serious presentation would have seemed out of place. Therefore, during the tea break session, we used some interesting stories from our daily research training to introduce our iGEM project and share some funny moments and experiences from our lab experiments. Finally, to liven up the camping atmosphere, we brought agar plates from our own laboratory and led everyone in microbial graffiti activities.</p>
<h3>Process</h3>
<p>The camping began, and together we set up tents and barbecue stoves. During the camping, we hiked together, discussing interesting stories about biology and research. We used light traps to catch moths, searching for fascinating creatures in nature. We also barbecued together, introducing our project and synthetic biology to the students while chatting.</p>
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/fig-35.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 21 Camping Activities</center></strong></p>
 
<p>We also conducted a microbiota graffiti activity where everyone collected samples from the riverbank and river water and drew patterns on agar plates. After a period of cultivation, we noticed that the colonies on one of the agar plates were connected, forming the shape of &quot;IGEM&quot;. The students were both surprised and delighted by this discovery.</p>
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/fig22.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 22 Microbial graffiti game</center></strong></p>
 
<h3>Feedback: How did our activities encouraged an open dialogue with audience?</h3>
<h4>For our camping-mates: what have they learnt from the activities?</h4>
<p>The camping activity was closely related to biology. Students explored various organisms such as inchworms, mayflies, leeches, etc., and in the process of getting close to nature, they experienced the unique joy of being &quot;biology enthusiasts&quot;. Through our discussions and interactions, more students began to understand iGEM and synthetic biology. They expressed curiosity about the work our team is engaged in and gave us high recognition.</p>
<h4>For CAU-China: what did we received from this activity?</h4>
<p>This camping activity allowed us to step out of the monotonous laboratory setting and experience the wonders and beauty of nature. Additionally, interacting with our fellow students during the camping trip was inspiring.</p>
<p>Furthermore, the microbiota graffiti activity left a deep impression on us. In order to prevent densely packed colonies on the agar plate, we prepared agar with kanamycin. However, the agar plate still had a significant amount of colonies. This insight reminded us that there are many bacteria in the environment with resistance. Therefore, we need to pay more attention to the standardization of sterile operations in our future experiments.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>Class Meeting Exchange</h2>
<h3>Target</h3>
<p>Students in the lower grade biology class.</p>
<h3>Activity Time</h3>
<p>September 17, 2023.</p>
<h3>Purpose</h3>
<p>September marks the beginning of a new school term, and students one grade lower than us are about to embark on their research and study journey. During this special period, we were invited to participate in a class meeting of one grade below us to share our experiences in research competitions. Seizing this opportunity, members of CAU-China team aim to provide an in-depth introduction to our project and engage in discussions about synthetic biology with the students.</p>
<h3>Preparation：Why did we design the activity in this way?</h3>
<p>For our younger peers, who have recently started their journey in biology, they might be feeling uncertain about their future direction in biological research or have doubts about how deeply they can delve into scientific research. During this class meeting, we used our team&#39;s own experiences as an example, showcasing the ideas and interim results of our project. This allowed the students to understand synthetic biology and iGEM while encouraging them to contemplate their own interests and directions. After the meeting, we also provided our contact information, hoping to engage in one-on-one discussions with more students to further explore their interests in depth.</p>
<h3>Process</h3>
<p>The presentation during this class meeting was divided into two parts. In the first part, our team leader, Zhu Wanying, and Xu Linjie introduced iGEM and synthetic biology. They used analogies such as circuits and building blocks to explain the basic principles of synthetic biology, portraying us as &quot;creators&quot; in the process of &quot;synthesizing&quot; living organisms. During the meeting, the team leaders also explained the content and procedures of the iGEM competition to attract more students to participate in iGEM in the future.</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/fig24.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 23 Team leaders introduce iGEM and synthetic biology</center></strong></p>
 
<p>In the second part, our team member Liu Xiangjun presented our project for this year. Students were amazed by the achievements we made in the areas of filamentation, crosslinking, and silicification. They recognized the high value of our materials.</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/fig25.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 24 Liu Xiangjun introduces our project</center></strong></p>
 
<h3>Feedback: How did our activities encouraged an open dialogue with audience?</h3>
<h4>For our younger peers: what have they learnt from the activities?</h4>
<p>Through thorough discussions, the students developed an interest in synthetic biology and expressed their admiration for our project. During the post-meeting discussions, we patiently addressed the students&#39; concerns and encouraged them to study diligently and be courageous in their pursuits.</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/fig26.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 25 Our communication with our younger peers after the class meeting</center></strong></p>
<h4>For CAU-China: what did we received from this activity?</h4>
<p>Different from the educational approach used for primary and middle school students, during this activity, we made efforts to present the full scope of our project. We delved into specific details, such as the principles behind the LuxR system activation and the SpyCatcher expression localization. Consequently, the feedback we received was much more detailed than before. Throughout the exchange about our project, we received affirmation and encouragement. While addressing their doubts, we also felt the value of the journey we have undertaken.</p>
