<h2>One-on-one Communication with Freshmen</h2>
<h3>Target</h3>
<p>Freshman college students.</p>
<h3>Activity Time</h3>
<p>August 22, 2023.</p>
<h3>Purpose</h3>
<p>At the beginning of the new semester, our school welcomed freshmen. On the orientation day, our team members volunteered to guide the freshmen around the campus. During this opportunity, we engaged in one-on-one conversations with the freshmen, introducing them to and familiarizing them with synthetic biology.</p>
<h3>Preparation：Why did we design the activity in this way?</h3>
<p>Unlike our peers in the same grade, the freshmen might not have a systematic understanding of biology and may not be aware of the frontier areas of life science. Therefore, for these students, we chose to engage in one-on-one conversations. During these interactions, we aimed to understand each student&#39;s understanding of biology and their plans for the future. Simultaneously, we expanded their horizons by introducing synthetic biology and our project, sparking enthusiasm for this field.</p>
<h3>Process</h3>
<p>On August 22nd, our school&#39;s welcoming event was in full swing. Amidst the crowd, two students could be seen talking and laughing, engaging in lively conversations. These scenes portrayed our CAU-China team members interacting one-on-one with the freshmen. While touring the campus, we introduced the students to the concept of synthetic biology and how it is applied. We escorted each new student to their dormitory and gifted them postcards made by our team.</p>
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/fig27.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 26 CAU-China team members guided the freshmen on a campus tour</center></strong></p>
 
<h3>Feedback: How did our activities encouraged an open dialogue with audience?</h3>
<h4>For the freshmen: what have they learnt from the activities?</h4>
<p>According to our survey, the majority of freshmen mentioned that they had never heard of synthetic biology before. After our introduction, the students were amazed and curious about this fascinating field. Such in-depth conversations also inspired students who are considering a future in synthetic biology.</p>
<h4>For CAU-China: what did we received from this activity?</h4>
<p>In this one-on-one exchange activity, we also felt the enthusiasm of everyone for biology, especially in the emerging field of synthetic biology. Our encouragement for them serves as encouragement for us as well. We will not forget our initial intentions and strive to make our project the best it can be. Only by doing so can we set an example for the freshmen.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>Open Laboratory Exchange Activitie</h2>
<h3>Target</h3>
<p>Undergraduate students in their first and second grade of university.</p>
<h3>Activity Time</h3>
<p>October 8, 2023.</p>
<h3>Purpose</h3>
<p>The so-called education is by no means just theoretical teaching and paper discussions; it must be combined with practical experience. In our daily university life, many students do not understand iGEM and consider our CAU-China team to be a very &quot;mysterious&quot; group. Therefore, to allow more students to approach synthetic biology and iGEM, experience our research and work firsthand, and to let students who have just started their research in biology understand the basic technical skills in the laboratory, we organized the Open Laboratory Exchange Activitie.</p>
<h3>Preparation：Why did we design the activity in this way?</h3>
<p>During the preparation for this event, we first considered that most people might not have a deep understanding of synthetic biology. Similar to our previous class sharing activities, we prepared a presentation on synthetic biology and an introduction to our project. Additionally, we wanted everyone to have a deeper understanding of our project&#39;s design. Therefore, we chose the crosslinking module&#39;s SpyTag pathway as an example to explain the experimental process from molecular cloning to phenotype construction.</p>
<p>In the experimental session, we aimed to validate whether the construction of the SpyTag pathway vector was successful or not through basic experiments like plasmid extraction and PCR. This allowed the students to gain hands-on experience and understanding of biological research experiments.</p>
<h3>Process</h3>
<p>In this event, we had the honor of inviting our team&#39;s advisor, Professor Yang Jinshui, to provide on-site guidance.</p>
<p>The session began with our team leader, Xu Linjie, introducing what synthetic biology and iGEM are, as well as our project. The students showed tremendous interest and enthusiasm, looking forward to our Jamboree journey and aspiring to participate in this exciting competition in the future.</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/a42.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 27 During the laboratory activity, Captain Xu Linjie introduced synthetic biology and our project</center></strong></p>
 
<p>Next, our experimental team leader, Huang Yaohan, explained the concepts of vectors and plasmids, the basic principles of plasmid extraction and PCR. Using our project&#39;s SpyTag pathway as an example, he walked everyone through the process of gene acquisition and vector construction.</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/a44.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 28 The leader of the experimental group Huang Yaohan explained the principles of the experiment</center></strong></p>
 
<p>Although the students participating in the lab activity had all passed the &quot;Lab Safety Exam,&quot; to further ensure everyone&#39;s safety, we provided disposable nitrile gloves and made sure everyone wore lab coats.</p>
<p>During the experiment, we printed and distributed the experimental procedures. Each lab station had a CAU-China team member providing guidance. Under the guidance of Huang Yaohan, the experiment proceeded smoothly, and the students successfully extracted pET-30a plasmids from <em>Escherichia coli</em> DH5α.</p>
<p>Next, our captain Xu Linjie demonstrated the method for preparing agarose gel electrophoresis gels. All the students watched carefully, learning attentively.</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/a45.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 29 Huang Yaohan guides everyone in configuring the PCR system</center></strong></p>
 
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/a46.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 30 Xu Linjie shows how to configure gel</center></strong></p>
 
<p>In the end, after PCR and electrophoresis, almost everyone obtained the correct experimental results—the Flgh-SpyTag fragment was successfully amplified from the pET-30a plasmid.</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/a47.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 31 Classmates&#39; electrophoresis results</center></strong></p>
 
<h3>Feedback: How did our activities encouraged an open dialogue with audience?</h3>
<h4>For the students: what have they learnt from the activities?</h4>
<p>The students gained a lot from this open laboratory experience. Some were amazed by the creativity of synthetic biology, while others felt the charm of biological experiments. Our CAU-China team&#39;s enthusiasm and efforts allowed more students to experience a sense of achievement and strengthened their determination to pursue a path in life science research.</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/a48.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 32 The feedback we received from our classmates on today&#39;s activity</center></strong></p>
 
<h4>For CAU-China: what did we received from this activity?</h4>
<p>This was the first time our team members acted as &quot;lab instructors&quot; and guided an experiment, and the successful event gave us a great sense of achievement. While guiding the students through the experiment, many of them were still unclear about the principles, leading to confusion and hesitation. Fortunately, they were willing to ask questions and solve problems under our guidance. This reminded us that in experiments, it&#39;s essential to think critically about the &quot;why&quot; rather than just memorizing without understanding.</p>
<p>During the waiting periods in the experiment, we engaged in deep conversations with the students. We discussed topics such as whether synthetic biology could only be applied to microorganisms. We encountered many students with a passion for biology and ambitious aspirations. We hope that in the future, we can work together to contribute significantly to the field of life sciences.</p>
