<br><br><div class="container"><div class="horizontal-line"></div></div><h1>Special Education – Picture Book Sharing</h1><div class="container"><div class="horizontal-line"></div></div>
<h3>Target</h3>
<p>Children at autism centers.</p>
<h3>Activity Time</h3>
<p>Late August to late September.</p>
<h3>Purpose</h3>
<p>In this special education segment, we participated in the &quot;Picture Book Sharing&quot; event organized by OUC-China. We approached children with autism, used illustrated picture books to tell the story of synthetic biology and our project, and provided them with coloring books. This initiative fully embodies iGEM&#39;s inclusivity and care for the world.</p>
<h3>Preparation：Why did we design the activity in this way?</h3>
<p>The &quot;Picture Book Sharing&quot; event was initiated by the OUC-China team and co-hosted by 11 teams including ours (CAU-China), BIT-China, and HainanU-China… In this event, we create black and white picture books for children with autism, which the children then color and doodle. For our team, we aim to present the key aspects of our project (filamentation, cross-linking, and silicification) in the form of cartoon drawings and stories, allowing the children to have a more vivid understanding of our project.</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/fig36.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 33 The black and white picture book we created</center></strong></p>
 
<h3>Process</h3>
<p>From the end of August to the end of September, we visited six different autism children&#39;s institutions together, bringing them an introduction to synthetic biology and engaging coloring activities with interesting picture books. The children all wore happy smiles.</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/ertongdama.png" width="600"/> </div>
