<br><br><div class="container"><div class="horizontal-line"></div></div><h1>Game Development – Targeting the General Public</h1><div class="container"><div class="horizontal-line"></div></div>
<p>Educational activities are not limited to schools and students. In order to showcase the charm of biology, especially synthetic biology, to the general public, we developed two games inspired by the basic logic of synthetic biology: &quot;I Want to Do Research&quot; and &quot;Synthesize Big-gene&quot;.</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/fig30.png" width="800"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 35 Game Development</center></strong></p>
 
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>&quot;I Want To Do Research&quot;</h2>
<h3>Our Source of Inspiration</h3>
<p>Our inspiration for developing this game comes from a popular board game called &quot;Monopoly,&quot; which is widely known among the public. Additionally, we combined it with the molecular cloning techniques frequently used in synthetic biology, giving our game a unique and interesting context.</p>
<h3>Design concept</h3>
<p>As a game aimed at the general public, we are committed to making the rules of the game understandable in simple language. We aim to enhance interaction and competitiveness among players through the purchasing rules of various components. Additionally, we intend to increase the unpredictability and fun of the game through the design of dice rolling and &quot;Chance&quot; events.</p>
<h3>Game Introduction</h3>
<p>A, T, C, G, four players, plan to conduct a synthetic biology - molecular cloning experiment to create a &quot;recombinant organism,&quot; hoping to express different genes in different organisms. However, their research funds are limited, and only by collecting the five essential components - chassis bacteria, plasmid, promoter, gene, and restriction enzyme, while avoiding bankruptcy, and successfully entering the &quot;laboratory&quot; area can they complete the experiment (win the game)! The player who completes the experiment first wins the game.</p>
<p>For more detailed rules, please refer to the &quot;Game Manual&quot;.</p>
