<h3>Game Effects</h3>
<p>After completing the board game, we first released it among children, teenagers, and university students. In our educational activities, we introduced the board game &quot;I Want to Do Research&quot; and guided everyone to play. Students brainstormed, searched for strategies, weighed pros and cons, and faced challenges on the road to &quot;research success.&quot; The small classroom transformed into a playground of knowledge and competition, where students found joy and excitement.</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/fig31.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 36 Players engage in the game &quot;I Want to Do Research&quot;</center></strong></p>
 
<p>In addition, our board game has received unanimous praise from the middle-aged and elderly population. They have shown strong interest in the game and are amazed at our ability to design a game that aligns so well with biology and is entertaining.</p>
<h3>Our Harvest</h3>
<p>For the members of CAU-China, this entertaining card and board game about synthetic biology not only brought joy to our research lives but also became an excellent tool for sharing the fascinating stories of synthetic biology with the public.</p>
<p>The development of this game was a novel experiment for us. It inspired us to think about how to incorporate fun elements into synthetic biology, making seemingly mundane nucleotide sequences and inconspicuous bacteria come to life in everyone&#39;s minds. This endeavor has encouraged us to explore new ways to engage the public and make science more approachable and enjoyable for all.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>&quot;Synthesize Big-gene&quot;</h2>
<h3>Our Source of Inspiration</h3>
<p>During our educational activities, despite our efforts to make the introduction of synthetic biology lively and vivid, it often remained confined to PowerPoint presentations, representing a one-sided output from us. Inspired by the idea that &quot;synthetic biology is about splicing different genes together to create new biological &#39;machines&#39;,&quot; we aimed to develop a game in the &quot;synthetic&quot; genre. This game would visually demonstrate this process, allowing the public to better understand synthetic biology while enjoying the gameplay.</p>
<h3>Design concept</h3>
<p>&quot;One gives birth to two, two gives birth to four, four gives birth to eight...&quot; Based on the exponential relationship with the number 2, we designed our game &quot;Synthesize Big-gene.&quot; The underlying logic of the game is that &quot;two identical components colliding with each other can &#39;evolve&#39; into another component,&quot; and so on. For example, two deoxyribonucleotide can synthesize cellulase gene, representing &quot;genes are composed of basic units called deoxyribonucleotide&quot;; two transcript RNAs can synthesize cellulase, representing &quot;the synthesis of proteins (enzymes) depends on the translation of RNA&quot;...</p>
<p>Furthermore, to enhance the game&#39;s fun and challenge, similar to the game &quot;Synthetic Big Watermelon,&quot; we allow players to freely manipulate the distribution of various components on the screen. This freedom enables players to explore different strategies to synthesize larger components.</p>
<h3>Game Introduction</h3>
<p>We have given the game &quot;Synthesize Big-gene&quot; a backstory: &quot;One day, a poor cellulose-degrading bacterium lost its cellulase gene due to its playful nature. As a result, it can no longer help humans digest cellulose in the intestines. Now, please help this pitiful probiotic by synthesizing cellulase and transforming it back into a powerful cellulose-degrading bacterium!&quot;</p>
<p>Players start from chemical elements and proceed to synthesize bases (A, T, C, G), deoxyribonucleotide (dNTP), cellulase genes, plasmid vectors, transcript RNA, and finally, the end product cellulase. When the components on the screen stack up beyond a certain height, the game ends, and the score is calculated.</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/fig32.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 37 &quot;Synthesize Big-gene&quot; game</center></strong></p>
 <center>
  <button ><a href="https://zhengzheng-15.github.io/Eng-creat/" target="_blank">Click here to play</a></button></center>

<h3>Game Effects</h3>
<p>After the game was developed, we first introduced it within the college student community of the same age group. While enjoying the fun, everyone also gained insights into synthetic biology.</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/fig33.png" width="400"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 38 Feedback from friends on our game</center></strong></p>
 
<p>Additionally, we brought this game to the Science Festival at Dandelion Middle School to share it with more people. The students were deeply fascinated by this fun game and were even reluctant to leave our booth. We took this opportunity to introduce synthetic biology to more teenagers. In the end, thanks to the overwhelming popularity of &quot;Synthesize Big-gene&quot;, our booth at the Science Festival received the &quot;Highest Popularity Index Award.&quot;</p>
 
<div align="center"> <img src="https://static.igem.wiki/teams/4614/wiki/education/fig34.png" width="600"/> </div>
<p> <strong><center>Fig. 39 Teenagers playing &quot;Synthesize Big-gene&quot; game</center></strong></p>
 
<h3>Our Harvest</h3>
<p>For us, &quot;Synthesize Big-gene&quot; is undeniably a fantastic game for leisure time. However, what brings us even greater joy is the experience it provides for the public. When people around us ask, &quot;Why is the plasmid behind the gene, and why is the enzyme behind RNA?&quot; we are more than happy to explain the principles of biology and the logic of synthetic biology to everyone.</p>
<p>The enjoyment of the game goes beyond the gameplay itself; it lies in this unique experience of synthetic biology!</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<br><br><div class="container"><div class="horizontal-line"></div></div><h1>Media and other activities</h1><div class="container"><div class="horizontal-line"></div></div>
<p>This year, our CAU-China team also used mass media to promote synthetic biology and our project to the entire society. In addition, we created numerous cultural and creative products to make synthetic biology more vivid, enabling more people to understand and appreciate the field.</p>
<h2>
  WeChat Official Account - "Zhongnong iGEM"
</h2>
<p>
  WeChat is the most commonly used social media app in China, where everyone browses and shares articles from WeChat official accounts. Therefore, our WeChat official account "Zhongnong iGEM" is our main way of publicity. Our account has more than 800 followers, and the articles we publish have been read over 3000 times. We use the official account to announce recruitment notices and team selection results. Through the official account, participants can sign up for education activities and read summaries of our events, enabling the public to be informed and participate in our educational activities. Additionally, we post project introductions and team introductions to let the public learn about our team and project.
We have also set up a quick access bar at the bottom of the official account. Through this bar, the public can easily play our mini-game "Synthesize Big-gene", or quickly find popular science articles published by CAU-China over the years.
We took over the official account platform from the previous team, and it will be passed on to all our future teams, recording the experiences of each iGEMer from CAU-China.
</p>
